passages.text: EQUITY: GENERAL CONSUMER
Commodity prices still trending downwards; companies with strong brands see SSSG growth in 2Q25

Commodity prices take a pause but still down y- y - positive for consumer margins Commodity prices have been largely trending down since the start of 2025 after their strong performance in 2024, but some of them recorded a pause in August. Lower prices for cocoa and stable prices for sugar should benefit F&B companies in Malaysia by lowering production costs. Major Malaysian F&B companies include Farm Fresh (FFB MK, Buy), Nestle Malaysia (NESZ MK, Not rated), F&N (FNH MK, Not rated) and Apollo Food (APOF MK, Not rated). We believe the continued decline in wheat and corn prices on a y- y basis should reduce input costs for companies such as QL Resources (QLG MK, Buy) and Farm Fresh. WMP prices have started to increase, but we think Farm Fresh's margins would be protected as it has adequate supply through Dec- 2025 and plans to lower its dependence on whole milk powder (WMP) for milk from 50% to 25- 30% going forward. Sharp m- m increase in coffee prices could impact margins for coffee suppliers and café operators. Major coffee suppliers in Malaysia include Nestle and café operators include Oriental Kopi (KOPI MK, Not rated) and Zus Coffee (unlisted).

Consensus EPS revisions largely a factor of Apr- Jun results announcementsConsensus EPS revisions over the past month have been a mixed bag and were largely a factor of recent company results. 99 Speed Mart (99SMART MK, Buy) reported strong revenue and net profit growth of \(12\%\) and \(22\%\) y- y, respectively, on the back of continued store expansion and SSSG improvement (see our 18 August report - 2Q25 beats estimates on higher revenue/margins). However, we think FY26F consensus estimates have been lowered marginally due to concerns over rising costs. MR DIY (MRDIY MK, Neutral) saw a marginal increase in revenue and net profit by \(2\%\) y- y each despite continued store expansion and higher gross margins with FY26F consensus revenue and net profit being lowered due to expectations of weaker sales growth (see our 13 August report - Weaker- than- expected 2Q on sharp SSSG decline). QL Resources (QLG MK, Buy) saw a slight decline in consensus FY26F estimates on weaker 1Q26 results along with concerns over the egg price subsidy removal and slower growth for the company's convenience store business (see our 27 August report - Weak 1Q26, but outlook improving). Consensus estimates for Farm Fresh (FFB MK, Buy) were relatively stable following strong set of 1Q26 results on the back of margin expansion (see our 28 August report - Gross margins to remain at \(\sim 32\%\) in FY26/27F).

Oriental Kopi (KOPI MK, Not rated) was one of the few companies with positive consensus estimates revision on the back of strong growth in revenue, net profit and gross margins q- q with a 9M25 SSSG of \(12.5\%\) . MSM Malaysia (MSM MK, Not Rated) recorded the biggest cut in estimates due to weaker results and concerns over an increased supply of liquid sugar from Thailand. Fraser & Neave (FNH MK, Not rated) reported a revenue and net profit decline of \(5\%\) and \(30\%\) y- y, respectively, due to weaker domestic sales and higher start- up losses from its dairy farm resulting in a cut to FY25F/26F consensus estimates. On the other hand, Dutch Lady (DLM MK, Not rated) reported a revenue and net profit increase of \(4\%\) and \(6\%\) y- y, respectively, but saw FY25F and FY26F net profit estimates lowered sharply due to higher raw material costs and higher promotion costs, in our view. Padini (PAD MK, Not rated)'s FY26E consensus estimates were lowered following the lowest 4Q25 net profit reported in the past 16 years amid concerns over lower spending from the core M40 population. Estimates for Carlsberg Brewery (CAB MK, Not rated) and Heineken Malaysia (HEIM MK, Not rated) were lowered due to concerns over potential tax increases on alcoholic products in Malaysia, in our view.
Malaysia ConsumerKriti Agrawal - NSFSPL

Retail sales and wholesale spending rose \(4.8\%\) y-y in June 2025 to MYR153bn (Fig. 1), backed by festive celebrations. Retail trade rose \(5.4\%\) y-y on expansion of sales in non- specialised stores including supermarkets, mini markets and convenience stores. Wholesale trade rose \(5.2\%\) y-y on higher sales of meat, poultry, eggs, rice, grains, flours, sugars, and bakery products. There was also strong growth recorded in household goods.

The Malaysian Ringgit (MYR) continued to strengthen, reaching 4.20/USD, marking its eighth consecutive month of gains, in line with Nomura's Economic team's forecast of USD/MYR at MYR4.20 in 2025F and MYR4.15 in 2026F (link). The MYR has benefited from several tailwinds, including strong foreign direct investment flow, growing current account surplus and fiscal consolidation efforts such as narrowing of the fiscal deficit and reduction in government debt. MYR has stayed fairly flat vs. CNY on a m- m basis. MYR's appreciation vs. CNY since the beginning of the year should benefit margins for consumer companies sourcing from China, such as Eco- Shop Marketing (ECOSHOP MK, Buy) and Mr.DIY (MRDIY MK, Neutral).

Cocoa prices (Fig. 8) eased a further \(9\%\) this month due to weaker demand from soft grindings in Europe and Asia. Improved near- term crop expectations versus earlier deficits also contributed to the decline, before weather headlines later in the month sparked brief rebounds. The continued decline in cocoa prices should benefit confectionery companies and producers of chocolate drinks such as Farm Fresh, in our view. Other major confectionery companies include Nestle and Apollo Food.

Corn prices (Fig. 10) have dropped \(1\%\) on m- m basis, due to strong supply from Brazil and Argentina, alongside ample US harvests. Weather conditions in the US remain favorable and exports from South America remain steady. Corn is increasingly used in the feed for a number of animals, including cows and poultry, and lower costs should benefit margins for Farm Fresh and QL Resources. Other Malaysian dairy and poultry companies include Dutch Lady, F&N and Leong Hup (LHIB MK, Not rated).

Global wheat prices (Fig. 9) have remained soft YTD and declined \(2\%\) m- m on the back of strong global harvests in the US, Russia, and Australia, supported by favorable weather and expanded acreage. While stock levels remain low, ample supplies from recent harvests have created downward pressure on prices. Lower wheat prices would be positive for margins for food companies - with major Malaysia ones being Apollo Food and Kawan Food (KFB MK, Not rated).

Crude oil prices (Fig. 14) have softened recently, down \(6\%\) m- m (- 9% YTD) following elevated prices across the past two weeks on supply worries emerging from the Russia Ukraine conflict. OPEC+ members recently agreed to accelerate production increases on 3 August. The 2.2 mb/d of production cuts announced in November 2023 and initially scheduled to be fully unwound by September 2026 will now be fully unwound by September this year. This increase should contribute to large inventory builds through 2026F, putting downward pressure on oil prices, in our view.

Whole Milk Powder (WMP) prices have risen about \(2.7\%\) m- m, rising about \(4.6\%\) since their recent bottom in July 2025 but still \(7.7\%\) below their recent peak in May 2025 (Fig. 5). The recent growth is driven by increased demand from China to replenish WMP inventories that are down \(63\%\) y- y on higher domestic consumption, in our view. Higher WMP prices should negatively impact the GMs of Farm Fresh as about \(50\%\) of its milk supply comes from WMP. Other major milk companies in Malaysia include Dutch

Coffee spikes \(31\%\) in August on tariff impact and worsening weatherCoffee prices spiked \(31\%\) m- m in August after the US imposed a \(50\%\) tariff on Brazilian coffee imports (from 6 August), disrupting trade flows and triggering a shift to non- Brazilian beans. This was further amplified by the weather, with Brazil seeing frost episodes and very dry conditions in Minas Gerais, adding supply risk. If coffee prices continue to rise, it should be negative for margins of coffee suppliers and café operators. Major coffee suppliers in Malaysia include Nestle and café operators include Oriental Kopi (KOPI MK, Not rated), Zus Coffee (unlisted).

CPO prices rise \(4\%\) m- m on stronger exportsCPO (crude palm oil) spot prices have risen about \(4\%\) m- m in August, largely due to stronger demand from India and Europe. Going forward, we see CPO prices trending upward due to higher prices of other edible oils, weak inventory levels in Indonesia and expectations of higher exports to major markets including India ahead of its festival season in October. If CPO prices continued to rise, it would negatively impact margins of most food and confectionery companies. Major Malaysian companies that operate in these segments include Nestle, Apollo Food and Kawan Food.

Soybean meal prices (Fig. 11) have strengthened \(9\%\) m- m on tighter availability tied to scheduled US crush- plant downtime/seasonal slowdown and a pick- up in export interest, which pushed meal futures up and lent pricing support to soybeans. Crushing activity is expected to undergo a slowdown into September, constraining meal supply. Active rerouting of Argentine meal cargoes within Asia also underscored regional demand flows. Higher soybean meal prices would be negative for QL Resources' livestock costs. Other Malaysian livestock companies include Leong Hup.

Egg prices (Fig. 12) have been on the downtrend across this year due to higher supply in peninsular Malaysia. The increase in supply has led the Malaysian government to gradually remove its egg price subsidy, down from MYR0.10/egg to MYR0.05/egg during 1 May- 31 July and zero subsidy from 1 August, with the ceiling price also removed. Egg prices have stayed relatively flat m- m, with Grade A eggs recording a \(1\%\) decline. If egg prices start to increase following the subsidy removal, it will be positive for revenue and margins of QL Resources, which gains \(\sim 10\%\) of its revenue from the sale of eggs. Other major egg producers include Leong Hup.

Sugar prices remain steady m- mThe sugar market has been broadly range- bound, with a slight net gain of \(1\%\) m- m. Support came from firmer crude oil (lifting ethanol prices and nudging Brazilian mills toward ethanol tightening sugar output) and Brazil center- south data showing late- July sugar production slipping y- y alongside lower field productivity. Offsetting that support were official forecasts of stronger 2025/26 crops in Brazil, India and Thailand, which capped rallies. Sugar is a key ingredient in many F&B companies and should prices dip lower on stronger crop expectations, it should further benefit margins of Farm Fresh's ice- cream business. Other major F&B companies that use sugar in their products include Nestle Malaysia, F&N and Apollo Food.

Malaysia's Energy Transition and Water Transformation Minister Datuk Seri Fadillah Yusof has said that the revised tariff structure ensures fair and equitable cost distribution across all users, while causing minimal changes for domestic consumers. Under the new structure, the details of energy charges, capacity charges, network charges and retail charges for each category are listed. The minister also noted that domestic consumers consuming less than 600kWh are exempt from the Automatic Fuel Adjustment (AFA) but those using more will be charged based on the cost of energy sources including gas and coal.

Our view: Investors have been concerned about the negative impact of higher electricity costs on consumer demand in the near term. However, we understand that about \(85\%\) of Malaysian households have seen lower electricity bills since the revised tariffs were applied in July 2025. Additionally, due to fuel and gas prices declining, for August 1 - 31, a rebate of 1.545sen/kWh will be applied to the bills. This should be positive for consumer demand, in our view.

Data released by the Department of Statistics Malaysia (DOSM) on 8 August showed the growing use of digital payments in June with a \(71\%\) y- y increase in electronic money transactions (link). Real- time retail payments platform transactions rose to MYR277bn, which highlights the expanding preference for fast and seamless fund transfer, according to the DOSM. Financial process exchange transactions also rose by \(11\%\) y- y with credit card spending remaining steady and debit card transactions growing \(3.9\%\) y- y.

Our view: The increase in digital payments in Malaysia highlights the increase in convenience and online shopping, in our view. We see this largely impacting the apparel lifestyle and electronics retail segment, with limited impact on both the daily essentials and luxury segments.

\(58\%\) of Malaysians are using AI technology for shopping, well above the global average of \(37\%\) , according to fintech company Adyen (unlisted) (link). According to the company, Malaysians are using ChatGPT and other intelligent search tools to discover new brands and products. \(71\%\) use AI for product inspiration and \(69\%\) have discovered new brands through it. Despite this, physical retail still holds strong appeal, with shoppers valuing the ability to see, feel and immediately purchase products. To balance these needs, \(55\%\) of the consumers want more engaging in- store experiences from Augmented Reality (AR) to Virtual Reality (VR) to in- store cafes, according to the article.

Our view: With Malaysians increasingly using AI and other technologies in their purchase process, we expect retailers to also increasingly adopt similar tools. We understand that currently about \(52\%\) of Malaysian businesses offer unified commerce, which merges online and offline process. These include allowing consumers to buy products online but return in- store or by in- store but have it shipped to home. To increase the speed of checkout, retailers are also rolling out one- click purchases, enhancing payment speed and installing mobile POS and tap- to- pay options. To prevent fraud, many Malaysian retailers also plan to invest in AI driven fraud prevention tools that can detect anomalies and confirm genuine users.

According to a 14 August article in Nikkei (link), US and other international brands, hit by the anti- Israel boycott, are implementing various strategies to minimize the impact including localization, price cuts and asset sales. Brands are emphasizing their local owners, workers and suppliers to build a stronger connection with the local community. These include promoting local products and services and ensuring operations are run by local management teams.

Our view: The steps taken by some international brands including localization and fostering a stronger connection with the local community appear to have made an impact, although we note that revenues and profitability for these companies are still below the levels seen in 2023. The boycott also led to the increased popularity of some domestic brands such as Farm Fresh (FFB MK, Buy) and Zus Coffee (unlisted) as Malaysians looked for alternatives to major international companies. This increased competition could continue to impact foreign companies in the longer term, in our view.

We believe 99SMART's superior earnings growth (FY24- 27F earnings CAGR of \(20\%\) ) vs global peers \((- 10\%)\) , high FCF generation and strong ROEs justify the higher valuation.
